4

Building an OBBTree

In this section we describe algorithms for building an OBBTree. The tree construction has two components: Ô¨Årst is the placement of a tight Ô¨Åtting OBB around a collection of polygons, and second is the grouping of nested OBB‚Äôs into a tree hierarchy. We want to approximate the collection of polygons with an OBB of similar dimensions and orientation. We triangulate all polygons composed of more than three edges. The OBB computation algorithm makes use of Ô¨Årst and second order statistics summarizing the vertex coordinates. They are the mean, , and the covariance matrix, , respectively [11]. If the vertices of the i‚Äôth triangle are the points i , i , and i, then the mean and covariance matrix can be expressed in vector notation as:

